Definition.WordDefinition: wad n 1: (often followed by `of') a large number or amount or extent; "a batch of letters"; "a deal of trouble"; "a lot of money"; "he made a mint on the stock market"; "it must have cost plenty" [syn: {batch}, {deal}, {flock}, {good deal}, {great deal}, {hatful}, {heap}, {lot}, {mass}, {mess}, {mickle}, {mint}, {muckle}, {peck}, {pile}, {plenty}, {pot}, {quite a little}, {raft}, {sight}, {slew}, {spate}, {stack}, {tidy sum}, {whole lot}, {whole slew}] 2: a wad of something chewable as tobacco [syn: {chew}, {chaw}, {cud}, {quid}, {plug}] v 1: compress into a wad; "wad paper into the box" [syn: {pack}, {bundle}, {compact}] 2: crowd or pack to capacity; "the theater was jampacked" [syn: {jam}, {jampack}, {ram}, {chock up}, {cram}] [also: {wadding}, {wadded}]
